          '<p><span style="background-color:#d9ead3;color:#000000;">Badwater Basin in Death Valley is the lowest point in the United States. It lies 86 metres below sea level, which creates an inhospitable environment</span><span style="background-color:transparent;color:#000000;">. During the summer, temperatures in this area often exceed 50 degrees Celsius, and it rarely receives any rainfall. Despite the searing heat and aridity of the region, it was once filled by a lake. Dubbed Lake Manly by geologists, its waters filled the valley during the Ice Age, forming a body of water that was 140 kilometres long and 180 metres deep. Lake Manly completely evaporated, leaving behind extensive salt flats, but it occasionally returns when extreme precipitation falls on nearby mountains and floods the basin. These temporary lakes are usually less than a metre deep, but they often attract tourists to Death Valley National Park when they appear.</span></p>',
